Would it make sense to rename the gdd specific types to something like ograf?
This:
```
{
  "type": "string",
  "gddType": "file-path",
  "gddOptions": {
    "extensions": ["txt", "json"] // [Optional, Array of strings] . Limit which files can be chosen by the user
  }
}

```
would become this:
```
{
  "type": "string",
  "ografType": "file-path",
  "ografOptions": {
    "extensions": ["txt", "json"] // [Optional, Array of strings] . Limit which files can be chosen by the user
  }
}

```
Or is this only cosmetics?

I did a local test, to see if I could get a font loaded in an OGraf in the [DevTool ](https://github.com/SuperFlyTV/ograf-devtool) (which uses shadow-DOM for rendering the WebComponents).

I was able to do so like this:

```javascript
[...]
load() {
  const myFontFace = new FontFace("Monsieur La Doulaise", "url(https://fonts.gstatic.com/s/monsieurladoulaise/v18/_Xmz-GY4rjmCbQfc-aPRaa4pqV340p7EZm5ZyEA.woff2)");
  document.fonts.add(myFontFace);
  await myFontFace.load()

  myElement.style.fontFamily = myFontFace.family;
}
[...]
```

([example is available here](https://github.com/ebu/ograf/tree/example/font-loading/v1-draft-0/examples/l3rd-name))

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a2fb9d8c-b750-4086-90e6-622c87cd0de2)


Since the `document` is a global variable, it should be available to use as-is? Or am I missing something?
